    "id": "nm0000164",
    "name": "Anthony Hopkins",
    "photo": "https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMTg5ODk1NTc5Ml5BMl5BanBnXkFtZTYwMjAwOTI4._V1_.jpg",
    "bio": "Sir Anthony Hopkins' parents were Muriel Anne (Yeats) and Richard Arthur Hopkins, a baker, who were both of half Welsh and half English descent. Influenced by , he decided to study at College of Music and Drama and graduated in 1957. In 1965, he moved to London and joined the National Theatre, invited by , who could see the talent in Hopkins. In 1967, he made his first film for television, .From this moment on, he enjoyed a successful career in cinema and television. In 1968, he worked on with . Many successes came later, and Hopkins' remarkable acting style reached the four corners of the world. In 1977, he appeared in two major films: with , , , , and , and . In 1980, he worked on . Two good television literature adaptations followed: and . In 1987 he was awarded with the Commander of the order of the British Empire. This year was also important in his cinematic life, with , acclaimed by specialists. In 1993, he was knighted.In the 1990s, Hopkins acted in movies like and , (nominee for the Oscar), , (nominee for the Oscar), , (nominee for the Oscar), , and . His most remarkable film, however, was , for which he won the Oscar for Best Actor. He also received a BAFTA for this role.",
