    "id": "nm0000133",
    "name": "Geena Davis",
    "photo": "https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BNTQ2YWM5MzAtYzlmNi00MmUzLWJmOTYtOWM2YTY0ZjE0OTcxXkEyXkFqcGc@._V1_.jpg",
    "bio": "As a child, Geena dreamed of being an actress. While in high school, she felt left out and had low self-esteem because, at 6 feet, she was the tallest girl in school. After high school graduation, Geena entered New England College in New Hampshire and then transferred the next year to Boston University, where she majored in drama. In 1979, she dropped out and moved to New York to start her career. Her career consisted of sales clerk and waitress. She worked at Ann Taylor, where she eventually rose to Saturday window mannequin while trying to get a job with a modeling agency. Eventually signed by the Zoli Agency, she wound up as a model in the Victoria Secret's Catalogue. Ever vigilant, was looking for new talent in the catalog when he spotted Geena and cast her in . With good reviews, Geena moved to Los Angeles where she was cast as Wendy in the short-lived but critically acclaimed television series with . Her next appearance on television was in her own series , which was also good, but soon canceled. Geena then returned to the big screen in the below-average followed by the successful movie . From there on, she was on a roll with husband in the horror remake . More successful were 's dark comedy and . For the last film, she was the surprise winner of the Oscar for Best Supporting Actress. More fun movies followed with the flying-saucer-in-the-pool and everyone-loves-a-clown with . The very successful , directed by , again garnered nominations for the Academy Award and Golden Globe. , with and directed by , was the turning point as her next film, , was only average. Then she married director and they set up a production and development company called \"The Forge.\" Their first film was , which flopped at the box office. Undeterred, Renny decided to film the big-budget , starring Geena as pirate leader Morgan, which also flopped. Geena has since starred in the thriller and played Eleanor Little in and . She's also returned to TV, headlining and . Both shows were canceled after one season, but she won a Golden Globe for the latter. In 2008, after being missed from the big screen for some years, Geena ventured to Sydney, Australia, playing the foul-mouthed mother of and to shoot the dark comedy .",
