    "bio": "Steve Martin was born on August 14, 1945 in Waco, Texas, USA as Stephen Glenn Martin to Mary Lee (née Stewart; 1913-2002) and Glenn Vernon Martin (1914-1997), a real estate salesman and aspiring actor. He was raised in Inglewood and Garden Grove in California. In 1960, he got a job at the Magic shop of Disney's Fantasyland, and while there he learned magic, juggling, and creating balloon animals. At Santa Ana College, he took classes in drama and English poetry. He also took part in comedies and other productions at the Bird Cage Theatre, and joined a comedy troupe at Knott's Berry Farm. He attended California State University as a philosophy major, but in 1967 transferred to UCLA as a theatre major.His writing career began on , winning him an Emmy Award. Between 1967 and 1973, he also wrote for many other shows, including and . He also appeared on talk shows and comedy shows in the late 1960s and early 1970s. In 1972, he first appeared on , doing stand-up several times each year, and even guest hosting a few years later. In 1976, he served for the first time as guest-host on . By 2016, he has guest-hosted 15 times, which is one less than 's record, and also appeared 12 other times on SNL.In 1977, he released his first comedy album, a platinum selling \"Let's Get Small\". He followed it with \"A Wild and Crazy Guy\" (1978), which sold more than a million copies. Both albums went on to win Grammys for Best Comedy Recording. This is when he performed in arenas in front of tens of thousands of people, and begun his movie career, which was always his goal. His first major role was in the short film, , which he also wrote. His star value was established in , which was co-written by Martin, and directed by . The film earned more than $100 million on a $4 million budget. He also starred in , , and , all directed by Reiner. To avoid being typecast as a comedian, he wanted do more dramatic roles, starring in , a film remake of 's 1978 series. Unfortunately, it was a financial failure.He also starred in 's , co-written by himself, opposite and . That year, he also appeared in the musical horror comedy, opposite . Next year, he starred in , co-written by himself, and in ' , opposite . His other films include and , both opposite Moranis. In 1991, he wrote and starred in , about a weatherman who searches meaning in his life and love in Los Angeles. It also starred his then-wife, . Same year, was so successful that a 1995 sequel followed.During the 1990s, he continued to play more dramatic roles, in , playing a traumatized movie producer, in , playing a fake faith healer, in , playing a betrayed man adopting a baby, and in 's thriller . Other, more comedic roles include in and , opposite , in 's , and in , written by himself and co-starring . After Bowfinger, he starred in and , both earning more than $130 million. He wrote and starred in , and appeared in the sequel of Cheaper by the Dozen. After them, he appeared in and , which he both co-wrote, as Inspector Clouseau.He continues to do movies, more recently appearing in , , and . Besides aforementioned, he has been an avid art collector since 1968, written plays, written for The New Yorker, written a well-received memoir (Born Standing Up), written a novel (An Object of Beauty; 2010), hosted the Academy Awards three times, released a Grammy award winning music album (The Crow: New Songs for the 5-String Banjo; 2009), and another album (Love Has Come For You; 2013) with . Since 2007, he has been married to Anne Stringfield, with whom he has a daughter.",
