    "id": "nm0000230",
    "name": "Sylvester Stallone",
    "photo": "https://m.media-amazon.com/images/M/MV5BMTA3MDY2ODk4ODVeQTJeQWpwZ15BbWU4MDY1ODc3MTgx._V1_.jpg",
    "bio": "Sylvester Stallone is an athletically built, dark-haired American actor/screenwriter/director/producer, the movie fans worldwide have been flocking to see Stallone's films for over 40 years, making \"Sly\" one of Hollywood's biggest-ever box office draws.Sylvester Stallone was born on July 6, 1946, in New York's gritty Hell's Kitchen, to (née Labofish), an astrologer, and , a beautician and hairdresser. His father was an Italian immigrant, and his mother's heritage is half French (from Brittany) and half German. The young Stallone attended the American College of Switzerland and The University of Miami, eventually obtaining a B.A. degree. Initially, he struggled in small parts in films such as the soft-core , the thriller and the comedy . He got a crucial career break alongside fellow young actor , sharing lead billing in the effectively written teen gang film . Further film and television roles followed, most of them in uninspiring productions except for the opportunity to play a megalomaniac, bloodthirsty race driver named \"Machine Gun Joe Viterbo\" in the -produced . However, Stallone was also keen to be recognized as a screenwriter, not just an actor, and, inspired by the 1975 Muhammad Ali-Chuck Wepner fight in Cleveland, Stallone wrote a film script about a nobody fighter given the \"million to one opportunity\" to challenge for the heavyweight title. became the stuff of cinematic legends, scoring ten Academy Award nominations, winning the Best Picture Award of 1976 and triggering one of the most financially successful movie series in history! Whilst full credit is wholly deserved by Stallone, he was duly supported by tremendous acting from fellow cast members , and , and director gave the film an emotive, earthy appeal from start to finish. Stallone had truly arrived on his terms, and offers poured in from various studios eager to secure Hollywood's hottest new star.Stallone followed with , loosely based on the life of Teamsters boss \"Jimmy Hoffa\", and before pulling on the boxing gloves again to resurrect Rocky Balboa in the sequel . The second outing for the \"Italian Stallion\" wasn't as powerful or successful as the first \"Rocky\", however, it still produced strong box office. Subsequent films and failed to ignite with audiences, so Stallone was once again lured back to familiar territory with and a fearsome opponent in \"Clubber Lang\" played by muscular ex-bodyguard . The third \"Rocky\" installment far outperformed the first sequel in box office takings, but Stallone retired his prizefighter for a couple of years as another series was about to commence for the busy actor.The character of Green Beret \"John Rambo\" was the creation of Canadian-born writer , and his novel was adapted to the screen with Stallone in the lead role in , also starring and . The movie was a surprise hit that polarized audiences because of its commentary about the Vietnam war, which was still relatively fresh in the American public's psyche. Political viewpoints aside, the film was a worldwide smash, and a sequel soon followed with , which drew even stronger criticism from several quarters owing to the film's plot line about American MIAs allegedly being held in Vietnam. But they say there is no such thing as bad publicity, and \"John Rambo's\" second adventure was a major money spinner for Stallone and cemented him as one of the top male stars of the 1980s. Riding a wave of amazing popularity, Stallone called on old sparring partner Rocky Balboa to climb back into the ring to defend American pride against a Soviet threat in the form of a towering Russian boxer named \"Ivan Drago\" played by curt in . The fourth outing was somewhat controversial with \"Rocky\" fans, as violence levels seemed excessive compared to previous \"Rocky\" films, especially with the savage beating suffered by Apollo Creed, played by , at the hands of the unstoppable \"Siberian Express\".Stallone continued forward with a slew of macho character-themed films that met with a mixed reception from his fans. was a clumsy mess, was equally mediocre, saw Rambo take on the Russians in Afghanistan, and cop buddy film just did not quite hit the mark, although it did feature a top-notch cast and there was chemistry between Stallone and co-star .Philadelphia's favorite mythical boxer moved out of the shadows for his fifth screen outing in tackling Tommy \"Machine\" Gunn played by real-life heavyweight fighter , the great-nephew of screen legend . Sly quickly followed with the lukewarm comedy , the painfully unfunny , the futuristic action film , and the comic book-inspired . Interestingly, Stallone then took a departure from the gung-ho steely characters he had been portraying to stack on a few extra pounds and tackle a more dramatically challenging role in the intriguing , also starring and . It isn't a classic of the genre, but certainly surprised many critics with Stallone's understated performance. Stallone then lent his vocal talents to the animated adventure story , reprised the role made famous by in a terrible remake of , climbed back into a race car for , and guest-starred as the \"Toymaker\" in the third chapter of the immensely popular \"Spy Kids\" film series, . Showing that age had not wearied his two most popular series, Stallone has most recently brought back never-say-die boxer Rocky Balboa to star in, well, what else but , and Vietnam veteran will reappear after a 20-year hiatus to once again right wrongs in the jungles of Thailand.Love him or loathe him, Sylvester Stallone has built an enviable and highly respected career in Hollywood, plus, he has considerably influenced modern popular culture through several of his iconic film characters.",
    "birthDate": null,
    "birthPlace": "New York's gritty Hell's Kitchen, to (née Labofish)",
    "knownFor": [
      "Rocky"
    ]
